Component 3: n8n Workflow Automations
Build using n8n skills available in the Claude Code project. The project has the following n8n skills that must be consulted when implementing any workflow:
n8n-mcp-tools-expert — for interacting with the n8n instance via MCP tools
n8n-workflow-patterns — for webhook-response patterns, error handling, and workflow structure
n8n-node-configuration — for configuring Google Calendar, Send Email, Gmail, and other nodes
n8n-expression-syntax — for date calculations, template expressions, and dynamic values in nodes
n8n-validation-expert — for input validation logic on webhook payloads
n8n-code-javascript — for Code node logic (slot generation, data transformation)
n8n-code-python — for Python-based Code nodes if needed
Always consult the relevant skills before building or modifying any workflow.
Instance: `https://n8n.srv983772.hstgr.cloud/home/workflows`
Workflow 1: Check Calendar Availability
Trigger: Webhook `GET /webhook/check-availability`
Flow:
```
[Webhook Trigger] → [Set Date Range] → [Google Calendar: Get Events] → [Filter Busy Slots] → [Generate Available Slots] → [Respond to Webhook]
```
Detailed Steps:
Webhook node — Path: `check-availability`, Method: POST, Response Mode: "Last Node"
Set node — Calculate date range:
If `preferred_date` is provided, check that single day
Otherwise, calculate next 3 business days from today
Define business hours: 9:00 AM – 5:00 PM
Define slot duration: 30 minutes
Google Calendar node — Action: "Get Many Events"
Calendar: Individual Google Calendar (configure OAuth2 credential)
Time Min: start of date range
Time Max: end of date range
Returns all existing events (busy times)
Code node (JavaScript) — Generate available slots:
Input: existing events + date range + business hours
Logic: Create 30-min slots during business hours, remove any that overlap with existing events
Skip weekends
Return max 6 available slots
Respond to Webhook node — Return JSON with `available_slots` array
n8n Skills Reference: Use `n8n-node-configuration` for Google Calendar node setup, `n8n-code-javascript` for the slot generation logic, `n8n-expression-syntax` for date calculations in Set nodes, `n8n-validation-expert` for input validation.
Workflow 2: Book Consultation
Trigger: Webhook `POST /webhook/book-consultation`
Flow:
```
[Webhook Trigger] → [Validate Input] → [Google Calendar: Create Event] → [Send Email: Lead Notification] → [Respond to Webhook]
```
Detailed Steps:
Webhook node — Path: `book-consultation`, Method: POST, Response Mode: "Last Node"
If node — Validate required fields exist: `customer_name`, `customer_phone`, `date`, `time`
If missing → Respond with error
Google Calendar node — Action: "Create Event"
Calendar: Individual Google Calendar
Summary: `"Sales Consultation — {{customer_name}}"`
Description: `"Phone: {{customer_phone}}\nEstimated storage: {{shipment_size}}\nBooked via AI Voice Agent"`
Start: Combine `date` + `time` into ISO datetime
End: Start + 30 minutes
Send Email node — Send lead notification email with booking confirmation details (name, phone, shipment size, booked time)
Set node — Build response with `booking_id` (use calendar event ID), confirmed details
Respond to Webhook node — Return success JSON
n8n Skills Reference: Use `n8n-workflow-patterns` for webhook-response pattern, `n8n-node-configuration` for Google Calendar Create Event, `n8n-expression-syntax` for datetime formatting, `n8n-validation-expert` for input validation logic.
Workflow 3: Send Lead Email
Trigger: Webhook `POST /webhook/send-lead-email`
Flow:
```
[Webhook Trigger] → [Validate Input] → [Send Email: Lead Details] → [Respond to Webhook]
```
Detailed Steps:
Webhook node — Path: `send-lead-email`, Method: POST, Response Mode: "Last Node"
If node — Validate `customer_name` and `customer_phone` exist
Send Email node (use n8n's built-in Send Email node or Gmail node)
To: your email address
Subject: `"New Crown Storage Lead: {{customer_name}}"`
Body (HTML):
```
     <h2>New Lead from AI Voice Agent</h2>
     <p><strong>Name:</strong> {{customer_name}}</p>
     <p><strong>Phone:</strong> {{customer_phone}}</p>
     <p><strong>Estimated Shipment Size:</strong> {{shipment_size}}</p>
     <p><strong>Notes:</strong> {{notes}}</p>
     <p><strong>Received:</strong> {{timestamp}}</p>
     <hr>
     <p><em>Sent automatically by Crown Storage AI Voice Agent via n8n</em></p>
     ```
Respond to Webhook node — Return success JSON
n8n Skills Reference: Use `n8n-node-configuration` for Send Email / Gmail node setup, `n8n-expression-syntax` for template expressions, `n8n-workflow-patterns` for error handling.
n8n Implementation Notes
No backend or database required — all lead data is sent via email, calendar events are the source of truth for bookings
All webhooks must use "Respond to Webhook" as the last node (not "When Called by Another Workflow")
Set webhook authentication to None initially for testing, then add header auth (`X-API-Key`) for production
Google Calendar requires OAuth2 credential — set up in n8n credentials with Calendar scope (individual calendar)
Email sending requires either SMTP credentials (for Send Email node) or Gmail OAuth2 (for Gmail node)
Use Error Trigger workflow for monitoring failures
All Code nodes should include try-catch blocks
Test each webhook independently with curl/Postman before connecting to ElevenLabs
Webhook Security (Production)
Once testing is complete, add header-based authentication:
```
Header Name: X-API-Key
Header Value: [generate-a-strong-key]
```
Configure the same key in ElevenLabs tool webhook headers.
